The program is functioned towards providing current, fundamental knowledge at a high interdisciplinary level, practical expertise in research techniques and the development of research problem management skills in graduates wishing to pursue an academic career or professional establishment in the industry or in the private sector.
The courses offered are designed to provide students with a comprehensive and in-depth knowledge associated with dental and craniofacial biomechanics, tissue engineering and applied biomaterials. In addition, the significant involvement of students in bibliographic and/or systematic reviews for the successful completion of their studies provides the opportunity to acquire high level interdisciplinary knowledge that will facilitate the completion of their laboratory practice and the performance of high quality research in the respective “cutting edge” fields. Students will be trained in critical evaluation of various types of scientific papers, management of bibliographic sources and organization of personal bibliography using modern tools (online applications, use of software such as Mendeley and Turnitin), planning for submission of proposals for competitive research projects and utilization of research tools and data, scientific writing and writing of research protocols and scientific papers, and understanding and application of legal rules, institutional frameworks and principles of bioethics and scientific ethics in: a) clinical research on humans (according to the “Declaration of Helsinki”), and b) laboratory research with experimental animals, use of material of human origin, potentially toxic substances/ microorganisms etc.
---
The program is suitable for both experienced and aspiring graduates who wish to enhance their careers. It is also appropriate for graduates who wish to pursue a research or academic oriented career in the fields of Biomaterials, Biomechanics and Tissue Engineering. After graduation students are eligible to work both in private research companies, institutes and laboratories or further pursue their academic development, applying for o PhD Thesis.
